section.subsection:
			 Sage Commands



 				When written as column vectors, vectors behave like n \times 1 matrices, and they can be coded as such in Sage. As a shortcut, you can specify the number of rows (number of entries in the vector) and then include a single list of the entries.
			
 			
 				
 					u=matrix(3, [2,4,6]);
					v=matrix(5, [1,3,5,7,9]);
					show(u);
					show(v)
 				
 			
			
			
				


				However, we often want to treat vectors as vectors specifically. In Sage, we use the vector command, which is similar to the matrix command. We do not need to state the number of entries with this command; we simply list them out. Note also that Sage displays the result in row form (an alternative display form discussed in the textbook), but they are treated the same as column vectors.
				
	 			
	 				
	 					u=vector([2,4,6]);
						v=vector([1,3,5,7,9]);
						show(u);
						show(v);
						v
	 				
	 			
				
				


				The cell below demonstrates how to create linear combinations of vectors. Note that writing "5v1" will cause an error; a multiplication symbol is needed between the scalar and the vector.
			
 			
 			
 				
 					v1=vector([1,-3,4]);
					v2=vector([2,5,1]);
					print(v1+v2);
					print(v1-v2);
					print(5*v1);
					print(3*v1+7*v2);
					print(-3*v1-4*v2)
 				
 			
			
			One nice consequence of Sage vectors is that we can easily create matrices out of them. We will usually want to create matrices whose columns are some given vectors. This is done using the column_matrix command and demonstrated below.
 			
 				
 					u1=vector([1,2,3]);
					u2=vector([4,5,6]);
					u3=vector([7,8,9]);
					A=column_matrix([u1,u2,u3]);
					show(A)

			 Sage Commands



 				Sage naturally understands multiplication of a vector by a matrix using the usual multiplication symbol (shift+8 on most keyboards). (Remember that Sage displays vectors in row form with parentheses, but correctly treats them as column vectors)
			
 			
 				
 					A=matrix([[1,2,3], [4,5,6], [7,8,9]]);
					B=matrix([[1,3,5], [7,8,9]]);
					v=vector([-1,3,-5]);
					show("A=",A," B=",B," v=",v)
					show("Av=",A*v)
					show("Bv=",B*v)
 				
 			
			


				Note that the dimensions have to match up (the number of columns of the matrix should match the number of entries in the vector); if they do not, then Sage will output an error (which you can see by executing the code below).
			
			
 			
 				
 					C=matrix([[1,2],[3,4], [5,6]])
					show("C=",C)
					v=vector([-1,3,-5]);
					show("v=",v)
					C*v
 				
 			
			
				
			
			As a reminder, if vectors are already defined, you can create a matrix using them. To make a matrix with the vectors as columns, use the column_matrix command, shown below. To make a matrix with the vectors as rows, just use the matrix command with the vectors given inside brackets.
 			
 				
 					u1=vector([1,2,3]);
					u2=vector([4,5,6]);
					u3=vector([7,8,9]);
					A=column_matrix([u1,u2,u3]);
					show("vectors as columns:",A)
					B=matrix([u1,u2,u3]);
					show("vectors as rows:",B)
